4th |next = 6th }} The 'Fifth United States Congress' was a meeting of the
legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the
United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives. It met at
Congress Hall in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania from March 4, 1797 to March 4, 1799,
during the first two years of John Adams's presidency.

The apportionment of seats in this House of Representatives was based on
the First Census of the United States in 1790. Both chambers had a
Federalist majority.
